41:05.479 --> 41:09.624
I happen to know this human being better than anyone else.

41:09.744 --> 41:17.873
On the other hand, I did take liberties with... I mean, I didn't... It's a novel.

41:17.974 --> 41:19.015
It's a novel.

41:19.615 --> 41:26.363
Yeah, there's enough of my own invention and filtering and sorting

41:27.170 --> 41:32.658
and the kind of cleaning up of the chronology, because you just can't transplant.

41:34.841 --> 41:50.724
But on the other hand, I benefited hugely from the fact that even when I was making something up, I could go out of my office, if it were Saturday or Sunday, and say, Alice, how would you tell this story?

41:50.944 --> 41:51.345
Really?

41:51.585 --> 41:54.409
Can you give me an example of this?

41:55.334 --> 41:57.337
And how it got into the book?

41:57.758 --> 41:58.419
Let's see.

41:59.240 --> 42:08.234
I should back up.

42:09.496 --> 42:24.278
The main way that the book took shape was that I had a certain fund of knowledge about what this kid was like.

42:24.697 --> 42:25.939
But that didn't help me very much.

42:26.239 --> 42:30.886
What I had really was... Do you mind if I shoot a couple of pictures of you while you're talking, by the way?

42:30.946 --> 42:33.109
No, not at all.

42:33.129 --> 42:33.370
Okay, good.

42:33.390 --> 42:34.732
I like the hand gestures.

42:34.812 --> 42:43.284
What I had were these interviews that I did of her after I'd pick her up at school.

42:44.166 --> 42:48.272
I'd take her out to a place we would have tea near this cathedral.

42:48.933 --> 42:50.335
What was the cathedral, by the way?

42:50.715 --> 42:53.860
Oh, it was the Ely Cathedral, E-L-Y, Ely, England.

42:54.835 --> 43:24.133
and uh we'd go out and do you mind if i do the uh glasses off for you whatever you like um anyway so we would get we would uh we would meet after these things about almost about two or three times a week i guess and i would just ask what ha what what happened that day

43:24.367 --> 43:31.738
And when she would answer, she just told it in her own words.

43:31.818 --> 43:33.761
And it was fascinating.

43:33.781 --> 43:36.565
So the next day, I would write a scene.

43:36.585 --> 43:38.628
And that's how the book mostly took shape.

43:39.189 --> 43:46.019
But then in the cleaning up, well, then I would get interested in certain stories and things.

43:46.039 --> 43:48.523
And then I would, sometimes I would tell her a story.

43:48.583 --> 43:49.685
I don't want to give an exact.

43:51.167 --> 43:51.808
We're here.

43:53.459 --> 43:54.240
We'll be here.

43:55.963 --> 43:59.869
Sometimes I would tell her.

43:59.909 --> 44:09.403
I actually want to keep it a mystery which stories in the book are my own and which stories are hers.

44:09.583 --> 44:10.164
Okay, that's great.

44:10.184 --> 44:12.928
Because... Yeah.

44:17.114 --> 44:22.302
There's a nice...

44:24.037 --> 44:25.459
So I would tell her a story.

44:26.400 --> 44:26.901
You don't?

44:27.161 --> 44:28.262
Yeah, I would tell her a story.

44:28.843 --> 44:34.390
And she has, I think, a much better memory for narrative than I do.

44:35.011 --> 44:40.778
I don't know if it's because when you're a kid you've heard fewer stories, or if it's just because she's better.

44:40.799 --> 44:44.283
I think it's just because she's better at this.

44:44.363 --> 44:49.309
So then a couple weeks later I'd ask her to tell me the story that I'd told her.

44:50.151 --> 44:53.655
And inevitably she told it better than I did.

44:54.243 --> 45:00.590
And so in some cases my own story is filtered through her own sensibility.

45:00.610 --> 45:02.473
And this is while you were in England?

45:02.613 --> 45:04.295
So it was written on the spot, yeah.

45:04.555 --> 45:05.296
The book was written.

45:05.336 --> 45:10.802
When she was in school in England, the book was written in that first term in England.

45:10.842 --> 45:13.906
So what was the motivation for it?

45:14.507 --> 45:15.748
Well, I don't know.

45:15.788 --> 45:23.457
I just felt that, oh, well, the motivation was that I could see that this

45:24.533 --> 45:35.649
this kid, that this kid I love so much, was changing every year.

45:35.689 --> 45:52.853
You know, she was, she, certain ways that she used to speak, certain phrases that she used to use were disappearing, especially the language, but also the, you know,

45:53.255 --> 45:55.378
You know, she was understanding things a little better.

45:55.418 --> 46:17.711
And I felt a little panicky about having, about the prospect of losing some of the ways that she'd understood the world and felt that, you know, I had a real deadline, that if I didn't write the book then, that a whole fund of things, that I would forget certain things that were true of her.

46:18.832 --> 46:21.456
And the only way really to keep this

46:23.022 --> 46:36.939
this particular person, to keep a memory of her the way she was at a certain time, was to write a novel about her.

46:37.860 --> 46:38.921
Why didn't you do it in her voice?

46:40.143 --> 46:52.017
Because I'm not very keen about books that are written in the first person and kids' voices, because I've never known a kid

46:52.385 --> 46:53.406
who can write a novel.

46:54.608 --> 47:05.160
One of the things that the heroine in my story does is write stories, and she has ambitions to write long things, books and everything, but they always end to be continued.

47:05.641 --> 47:11.247
Because the salient thing about being a kid is that you're not going to write 200 pages.

47:11.287 --> 47:18.055
You're going to write seven pages and then be excited about the grand plan that never comes to fruition.

47:18.760 --> 47:31.438
So it has to be somewhere in that middle space between a third person and a first person, because it has to have a grown-up stick-to-itiveness that would result in a finished book.

47:33.081 --> 47:40.632
Also, I don't think it's just too easy to have.

47:41.192 --> 47:44.397
I mean, children don't even think in

47:44.680 --> 47:45.821
chapters in novels.

47:46.762 --> 47:48.284
So it has to be third person, I think.

47:48.304 --> 47:48.885
Anyway, go ahead.

47:48.985 --> 47:51.087
No, that's an excellent answer.

47:51.408 --> 47:54.671
You know, it's said that if J.D.

47:54.691 --> 47:59.637
Salinger were to write Catcher in the Rye today, it would be classified as a young adult novel.

47:59.697 --> 48:07.446
I mean, this is one of the risks you take in having your sensual character, your protagonist, being an adolescent.

48:08.587 --> 48:14.113
Were you mindful of any kind of, I hesitate to use the word risk, but I mean,

48:15.207 --> 48:21.173
Yeah, I'm talking about the business of writing now, not about the perception of the novel itself.

48:21.834 --> 48:24.957
The fact that you are writing this from the viewpoint of a child.

48:25.497 --> 48:42.835
Well, yeah, the other thing that I am always suspicious of is when the way that a writer attempts to prove that his book about a child is really for adults is that he uses the child's

48:43.388 --> 48:51.339
point of view to illuminate some dark truth about parental reality or about political upheaval or something like that.

48:51.980 --> 48:56.927
In other words, there's a deep, unhappy, unsettling thing in the middle of this book.

48:57.007 --> 49:00.412
Therefore, it's for adults.

49:02.135 --> 49:04.658
That also just seems false to me.

49:04.698 --> 49:06.841
It's too easy.

49:06.861 --> 49:12.349
If you do it right, if you can

49:12.548 --> 49:16.011
really do justice to the way a kid thinks.

49:16.972 --> 49:39.655
It's not that you're going to get a way of thinking that's superior to grown-up thinking, but you're going to get a particular completeness of understanding and misunderstanding that is intrinsically fascinating and worth studying just as a kind of case study of moral development.

49:39.675 --> 49:41.897
I mean, that's really what was

49:43.497 --> 50:12.711
was part of what I liked was all the, in addition to the verbal oddities and in some cases I thought felicities, at the childish texture of the book there was this fierceness on the part of the heroine

50:13.754 --> 50:18.540
to defend another girl who was persecuted.

50:18.580 --> 50:22.825
Obviously, there are many worse things that happen in the world.

50:23.666 --> 50:40.808
This is a very tame complication, but I've never been able to... I don't know anything about the really bad things, you know, airplane disasters,

50:41.378 --> 50:47.364
divorces or things like that, or massacres.

50:47.505 --> 51:01.139
I mean, the scale that a child lives on is a scale in which if somebody is being bullied, that's a disaster.

51:01.840 --> 51:03.342
And I think it is a disaster.

51:03.402 --> 51:08.247
I mean, I think we are very lucky to live in a culture in which

51:08.986 --> 51:22.046
an Anglo-American culture in which if a kid is made to cry because other kids in the school are kicking her, that's a very bad thing.

51:22.166 --> 51:30.879
I mean, I think we're fortunate there, but the scale doesn't matter in the sense I'm saying.

51:31.460 --> 51:37.609
If you can successfully scoop up some of the moral

51:39.698 --> 52:01.723
dimension of childhood and how a child has to sift through the claims of other children and what her parents think are right and all the stories that she has is kind of moving around in her head of how other people have acted.

52:01.743 --> 52:09.452
