55:44.116 --> 56:00.820
But even then I wanted to be sure, and so she would tell the story back to me, and then sometimes I would incorporate a particular way that she told it rather than I felt like one of those guys like Prop, you know, who did the metamorphosis of folktales or something.

56:01.060 --> 56:13.498
In a strange way, I felt like an anthropologist or something rather than a novelist that's quite as much, although I wanted to have this kind of

56:14.221 --> 56:21.934
complicated, realistic texture that only a novel can have, you know.

56:22.535 --> 56:24.919
I haven't really questioned you about the novel itself.

56:25.500 --> 56:27.584
I try not to do that with novels.

56:27.664 --> 56:33.794
I read them and it's my business to, you know, if it seems like we're not discussing the novel.

56:34.175 --> 56:35.197
We are discussing it.

56:35.217 --> 56:37.140
But I mean in terms of the actual

56:37.306 --> 56:39.048
Right, right.

56:39.930 --> 56:43.054
Well, I mean, you seem to know what it's about.

56:43.094 --> 56:45.157
It's about a nine-year-old person.

56:45.197 --> 56:47.099
It doesn't bother me in life.

56:47.119 --> 56:52.447
As long as you understand how I, you know, I have a responsibility here to read it.

56:52.507 --> 57:00.538
I did two interviews in Denver, both of which were with people who had not read the novel at all.

57:00.658 --> 57:01.699
I mean, they looked at the cover.

57:02.541 --> 57:03.442
They were honest about it.

57:03.722 --> 57:05.845
And that actually can work okay, too.

57:06.365 --> 57:07.526
Well, if they're honest about it.

57:07.686 --> 57:08.947
Yeah.

57:08.967 --> 57:16.655
If they don't pretend to— Because then it becomes the kind of conversation you'd have at a party or something, where the person says, what do you do?

57:16.715 --> 57:17.796
And you say, oh, well, what's it about?

57:17.816 --> 57:18.496
What's it about?

57:18.516 --> 57:19.177
Don't you love that?

57:20.578 --> 57:20.678
Yeah.

57:20.698 --> 57:23.341
Richard Ford answers, it's about 432 pages.

57:25.183 --> 57:27.024
I don't mind at all.

57:27.144 --> 57:31.388
I mean, I like this—they get a kind of weird look, but I say, well, what kind of books do you write?

57:31.469 --> 57:36.253
And I say, well, the first one was about this guy who went out to buy his shoelaces on his lunch hour.

57:36.892 --> 57:45.563
So I was going to kind of look around and, oh, interesting, thinking, well, it's fine.

57:45.583 --> 57:47.805
I get involved when I was writing General Madness.

57:47.825 --> 57:49.027
I said, this is Miami.

57:49.047 --> 57:51.670
I was at the book fair down there last year.

57:52.591 --> 57:55.555
My old pal Bill Robinson from the Miami Herald was out there.

57:55.575 --> 57:59.760
We used to hang out and drink, you know, in New York.

58:00.466 --> 58:03.418
My friend Bill Robinson here, he'd say, what's your book about?

58:03.458 --> 58:04.783
I said, well, it's about book collectors.

58:04.824 --> 58:07.193
And I said, and Bill was as guilty as the next guy.

58:07.213 --> 58:08.940
I said, I get this blank, vacant look.

58:09.173 --> 58:14.838
And then he came up to me after and he says, Nick, he says, the reason you get the plane for it is we were both drunk.

58:15.439 --> 58:22.566
He says, it wasn't because I wasn't comprehending what the book was about because I think we were drunk.

58:23.266 --> 58:24.848
He says, when you told me.

58:24.868 --> 58:25.469
Funny story.

58:25.489 --> 58:27.390
But I mean people say, what's this book about?

58:27.430 --> 58:31.694
And I say, well, it's about book culture, you know, it's about libraries.

58:32.355 --> 58:35.138
Well that's kind of interesting, you know, they say.

58:35.158 --> 58:37.560
Well that's a good way to say it.

58:38.047 --> 58:39.889
It's not a millennial thing, but it is.

58:39.909 --> 58:42.231
I'm not going to have millennium in the subtitle.

58:42.251 --> 58:43.532
That's the kiss of death, I think.

58:45.454 --> 58:48.397
I've changed the title three times.

58:48.417 --> 58:50.599
That's a very good question.

58:51.901 --> 58:57.706
Penelope Fitzgerald, she said she can't start writing, and she's strictly a pen and ink writer.

58:58.907 --> 59:04.133
And she said, I can't write until I have the first paragraph and the last paragraph and the title.

59:04.173 --> 59:05.674
She said, they always change my titles.

59:06.025 --> 59:09.549
But for me, I have to have all of these things.

59:10.330 --> 59:18.259
And then I said, well, gee, that's really quite an acknowledgment because you've written nine novels and only one has what could be described as a happy ending.

59:19.000 --> 59:21.122
And she said, well, I take my cues from life.

59:23.505 --> 59:29.051
But I guess yourself, do you kind of know the arc of the novel?

59:29.111 --> 59:34.277
Well, more so in the case of the earlier books, because I knew, say, with the mezzanine,

59:34.477 --> 59:41.526
I had all this stuff saved up that I'd been harboring for years that I wanted to put in one book.

59:42.928 --> 59:52.500
But with The Everlasting Story of Nori, I had no idea how the book was going to turn out because I was writing it day to day based on reports I was getting from the field.

59:52.761 --> 59:53.922
That's great.

59:54.403 --> 59:56.906
So I didn't know if it was going to have a happy ending or not.

59:56.926 --> 59:59.570
So this was quite literally a work in progress, wasn't it?

01:00:00.010 --> 01:00:04.416
Yeah, and I was hoping that things would end all right.

01:00:04.919 --> 01:00:18.439
And I mean, I had to make a few adjustments based on the fact that the characters don't exactly correspond to characters in real life.

01:00:18.539 --> 01:00:32.800
But I was kind of crossing my fingers that life would turn out all right, so that my book would have some kind of an ending.

01:00:34.383 --> 01:00:52.980
And I loved that feeling of, you know, skateboarding almost, through the giving, working, winding my way around whatever obstructions and park benches would come in my way.

01:00:53.020 --> 01:00:57.644
You know, the feeling that you're feeling your way through something without knowing what's going to be next.

01:00:57.725 --> 01:00:58.505
Did you have your title?

01:00:59.526 --> 01:01:03.630
Well, the title, the title is also the riskiest title, I think, because

01:01:04.555 --> 01:01:11.942
Because the everlasting story of Nori is just a strange-sounding thing.

01:01:11.962 --> 01:01:20.010
But it's true, I think, to a nine-year-old mind.

01:01:20.331 --> 01:01:34.545
The words like everlasting and forevermore and never-ending have a kind of power over this girl in the book.

01:01:36.770 --> 01:01:48.068
And she very much wants her heroines to have these lives, these heroic lives, and all these adventures.

01:01:48.149 --> 01:02:00.769
But of course she herself is having a fairly unadventurous life, going to school, studying, learning about classics, you know.

01:02:03.247 --> 01:02:05.329
So there's that part of the title.

01:02:05.670 --> 01:02:23.910
But the part that appealed to me maybe was the kind of sadness in it that every parent feels, that they love the self that their child is going to develop into, even in advance.

01:02:24.390 --> 01:02:33.000
I mean, I love the nine-year-old self that has annihilated the four-year-old self in my life.

01:02:33.318 --> 01:02:34.500
daughter.

01:02:34.801 --> 01:02:46.963
But all these series of cells that is a person developing are fleeting.

01:02:46.983 --> 01:02:50.770
They are very short-lived.

